    <text id="B0045T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>This letter of unknown provenance, describes what a James Wait claims a Mr.
                    Burdett owes his niece, Dorcas Wait.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
               

                <opener>
                    
                    <salute>Sir.</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>Went in <abbr expan="February">Feb</abbr>-<abbr expan="March">Mar</abbr> and left
                    at <abbr expan="Christmas">Xmas</abbr> 1866</p>

                <p>James Wait desires me to make a memorandum of the articles Mr. Burdett gave his
                    sister <add hand="h1" place="inline">Dorcas Wait</add> last year when she was
                    living with him.</p>

                <p>One new calico dress<lb/> One <orig reg="muslin">mouslaine</orig> dress a second
                    one belonging to one of his daughters<lb/> also a <unclear>linsay</unclear>
                    dress which was taken from her and a pair of shoes at $2.50 he was to pay her $4
                    per month and she lived there ten monthshe also gave her a shaker at 50<hi
                        rend="super">ct</hi>.</p>

                <p>If Mr. J. is not at home James Wait would be very glad if you would get the money
                    for his sister and enclose it to Mrs. M. Tate, Greenville he has been trying all
                    year and has entirely failed.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed/>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
